	<article id="post-368" class="post-368 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-uncategorized tag-management tag-professional-development">
		<header class="entry-header">
						<h1 class="entry-title"><a href="http://facio.com/blog/2012/09/handle-with-care/" title="Permalink to Handle with care" rel="bookmark">Handle with care</a></h1>
			
						<div class="entry-meta">
				<span class="sep">Posted on </span><a href="http://facio.com/blog/2012/09/handle-with-care/" title="12:00 pm" rel="bookmark"><time class="entry-date" datetime="2012-09-11T12:00:03+00:00" pubdate>September 11, 2012</time></a><span class="by-author"> <span class="sep"> by </span> <span class="author vcard"><a class="url fn n" href="http://facio.com/blog/author/dirk/" title="View all posts by Dirk" rel="author">Dirk</a></span></span>			</div><!-- .entry-meta -->
			
<!--			--><!--			<div class="comments-link">-->
<!--				--><!--			</div>-->
<!--			-->		</header><!-- .entry-header -->

				<div class="entry-content">
			<figure class="alignleft" style="width: 300px;"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-488" title="Albert Einstein" src="http://facio.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/Einstein.png" alt="Albert Einstein" width="300" height="375" /><br />
<figcaption>If Albert Einstein worked for you he might demand to work from home and get detailed financial info. He would be worth it.</figcaption>
</figure>
<p>Your best and most valuable employees are also the hardest to ultimately keep. That&#8217;s because the same things that make them so effective for you make them most desirable to the market and less tolerant to survive in a situation not commensurate with the high esteem they likely have for themselves. Since these are the people who create the most value for your organization this is not only frustrating but deserving of the highest strategic importance.</p>
<p>With that in mind, here are some tips to consider when thinking about how to best attract and retain top talent:</p>
<p>1. Make sure they are fairly compensated. The reality is that the best people know what they are capable of making, and what they are willing to take in the right situation. Trying to employ efficiency methods to constrain their compensation &#8211; a tactic which can work for younger employees and lesser performers &#8211; will surely lead top people to leave sooner or later.</p>
<p>2. Care about their development. While some of their development can and should be focused on how they benefit your company, you also need to help them grow in ways that will not clearly plug into your organization. They want to feel empowered and encouraged, not controlled and directed. Be proactive in helping them figure out where they want to go with their lives and contributing to their process of getting there.</p>
<p>3. Provide transparency. Top performers want to feel like they know what is going on, and have the ability to evaluate for themselves whether authority figures are making good decisions. You do not need to publicly share every shred of company information; what you must do is let them know that most information is available to be shared, then be prepared to share it if they ask to do so. While this seems like the potential to be a distraction, in reality an employee who is incessantly asking to see information likely isn&#8217;t the sort of high performer you want to keep anyway.</p>
<p>4. Allow them to be involved in decision making. Even if they don&#8217;t have the last word, they expect to be genuinely listened to and have their input factored into the final decision. Make sure they are in an environment and under a manager that is inviting of their input.</p>
<p>5. Trust them. These are different times, with flex hours, working from home and a remote workforce now the standard in more progressive companies and industries. The best people will often have expectations that would have seemed ridiculous even a decade ago, and very well might make you uncomfortable. Well, tough. This is the new normal. If you want to keep them and get the best out of them, you need to take a deep breath and trust them. Most high performers, and all truly exceptional employees, are deserving of your trust.</p>
<p>One easy way to think about your key employees is how you would a romantic partner. If you truly want to be with them long-term you need to invest with the relationship and &#8211; crucially &#8211; give them space, control and consideration. You must see them as their own people who will be less likely to leave if you reinforce, and even encourage, their freedom to do exactly that.</p>
					</div><!-- .entry-content -->
		
