                	</article><!-- #post-368 -->
		
								
							
	<article id="post-366" class="post-366 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-uncategorized tag-alignment tag-professional-development">
		<header class="entry-header">
						<h1 class="entry-title"><a href="http://facio.com/blog/2012/09/re-thinking-rejection-2/" title="Permalink to Re-thinking rejection" rel="bookmark">Re-thinking rejection</a></h1>
			
						<div class="entry-meta">
				<span class="sep">Posted on </span><a href="http://facio.com/blog/2012/09/re-thinking-rejection-2/" title="12:00 pm" rel="bookmark"><time class="entry-date" datetime="2012-09-04T12:00:32+00:00" pubdate>September 4, 2012</time></a><span class="by-author"> <span class="sep"> by </span> <span class="author vcard"><a class="url fn n" href="http://facio.com/blog/author/dirk/" title="View all posts by Dirk" rel="author">Dirk</a></span></span>			</div><!-- .entry-meta -->
			
<!--			--><!--			<div class="comments-link">-->
<!--				--><!--			</div>-->
<!--			-->		</header><!-- .entry-header -->

				<div class="entry-content">
			<figure style="width: 300px;" class="alignleft"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-574" title="Donald Trump" src="http://facio.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/trump-300x242.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="242" /></p>
<figcaption>We&#8217;ve been taught that rejection is humiliating and embarrassing. It shouldn&#8217;t be.</figcaption>
</figure>
<p>We&#8217;ve been taught that rejection is among the most painful things we will feel in our lives. Rejection sucks. Rejection hurts. It represents failure, lack, falling short, something being wrong with you. On a list of the things we most fear or dislike, for many of us, rejection would be on that list.</p>
<p>How unfortunate.</p>
<p>Rejection is re-alignment. Rejection is validation that something didn&#8217;t fit: a partner, a job, a career path, a university. Whether you are the leaver or the leave-ee, ultimately to reject or be rejected is not a referendum on what was rejected. It is simply a process of moving both sides closer to alignment. Rather than being a bad thing, it is among the very best of things. It represents progress, better outcomes, better realities.</p>
<p>Yes, I know: some of you who have felt particular pain at one rejection or another are skeptically folding your arms and furrowing your brow. I don&#8217;t blame you. I remember my most painful rejections so very well, permanently burnt into my brain. And the pain they caused was immense. The question is: was that pain necessary, or was it a product of my unrealistic framing of the context I was in?</p>
<p>While my feelings were very valid, honestly deconstructing those moments, the framing that caused that pain was not. When I&#8217;ve had difficult break-ups, the pain I felt ultimately had little to do with me so adoring the relationships and everything to do with my ego being bruised, my expectations being shattered, my private self feeling embarrassed, and other internally constructed factors that had little bearing on whatever it was that was ending. I may have rationalized it in other ways at the time, but stripping back the constructed layers to the truth, the self-imposed nature of the pain was clear. I can&#8217;t deny that.</p>
<p>These days, when I look in the mirror I see sprouts of grey in my beard and wisps of grey in my hair. With those signs of physical age have come perspective and understanding of deeper realities. Every relationship I had that gutted me when it ended, I now look back and acknowledge that end was for the best. In most cases, I think it should have ended sooner. The two academic programs I applied to and was rejected from in my career, which made me feel foolish at the time, in retrospect I am so appreciative for. They weren&#8217;t good fits. The gatekeepers recognized that, and they kept me out. Good. What would have been lost by my spending that time in that situation?</p>
<p>Today I embrace rejection. And I am far faster to &#8211; kindly, thoughtfully, empathetically &#8211; do the rejecting. It is a good thing. It is a critical part of the process for achieving better alignment. Each of us, as individuals or organizations, have wonderful outcomes waiting for us. We also have many, many more suboptimal outcomes, ranging from still pretty good to absolutely shambolic. Lord knows we don&#8217;t need &#8220;optimal&#8221; outcomes in our lives, but we also shouldn&#8217;t blindly accept something less just because it is there. We most seek out alignment and resonance with the places, people and ways we spend our time. We should feel empowered to reject others to help them and ourselves find our right level. When we are rejected, rather than wallow in self-pity or lash out in retaliation, we should honour and respect that which rejected us &#8211; if we didn&#8217;t respect and honour them we certainly shouldn&#8217;t feel hurt by their rejection &#8211; and reflect on why there was not a fit. Thereby, we will grow and learn. Thereby, we will find our best place and selves.</p>
<p>Thereby, we will find alignment, success and satisfaction. There is nothing sad about that.</p>
					</div><!-- .entry-content -->
		
